node.text:
TRUTH: surgery has not only made me a better shooter, but tremendously changed my appreciation for guns. Let me explain. First: yes this is a new @waltherarms PDP and yes, it is everything it’s cracked up to be. I didn’t think they could improve upon the PPQ much, and I’ve instead come to realize that I was an ignorant peckerwood. Most importantly, in recovering from surgery, with very, VERY limited mobility, practicing at the range was about one of the only activities I could do, and so I did it a lot. For future reference, I don’t recommend getting thoracic surgery amidst the worst/most expensive ammo shortage in modern history but that’s beside the point. In being so physically incapacitated and yes, feeling pretty physically vulnerable, I really did gain appreciation for “the great equalizer.”

What about the permanently incapacitated, the infirm, or really, even ANY average woman forced into a physical confrontation with a large man? Not only is a firearm an equalizer, but in all reality, it’s their only shot of getting out alive. Thank God we live in a country that recognizes their right to protect themselves (notice I didn’t say “affords” or “grants”). I also learned that no matter what’s going on, you can always find a way to improve at SOMEthing. For me, for two months, a big part of that was marksmanship. And while I’m no half-Asian lawyer YET, I’m on my way! … at least I will be when ammo prices come down. #sundaygunday #ad

node.text: Only a few years ago, on September 11th, 2001, we would all say, “never forget.” But we now have a generation of Americans who had yet to be born on that fateful morning. This generation is now entering your colleges. So, for those who’ve never experienced the horror of 9/11 in real time, please consider yourself extremely blessed. And never allow comfort to create complacency. Never allow good fortune to breed ingratitude. Because for all of us alive on that awful day, it was clear as day that not only can we lose our most loved ones in an instant… but that we are always one mere generation away from losing our freedoms forever. Just because you haven’t had to fight for yours yet, doesn’t mean that you won’t be called upon. Because many great men and women before you were. And they answered honorably. #AlwaysRemember #NeverForget
